Former head of Brazilian presidential cabinet brought to court
On Tuesday, a federal judge accepted charges against the former head of the Brazilian presidential cabinet for his alleged involvement in a massive corruption scheme involving the state oil company Petrobras.
The federal prosecutor's office said Jose Dirceu would be sued for allegations of corruption, fraud and money laundering brought this month.
Fourteen others will be tried, including Joao Vaccari Neto, former Treasurer of the Workers' Party, in power in Brazil, and Renato de Souza Duque, former president of Petrobras' business services.
Dirceu is the oldest member of the ruling Workers' Party taken into custody for ties to this scheme.
Dirceu served as chief of staff of former President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva between 2003 and 2005.
He was arrested in early August at home, where he was already under house arrest, with an 11-year sentence for involvement in a scheme to buy votes in Congress more than 10 years ago.
Prosecutors said Dirceu developed the bribe-making scheme at Petrobras, accepted bribes while in office and continued to receive payments from entrepreneurs after being closed in late 2013 for the vote-buying scandal.
According to prosecutors, the Petrobras scheme involved about $2 billion in bribes and other illegal funds.
Part of that money would have returned to the campaign fund of the ruling party and its allies.
It would also include bribes to Petrobras directors in exchange for inflated contracts.
"Miracle" recovery of a surviving student of the Peshawar massacre
A paralysed teenager after being shot four times in Pakistan's worst terrorist attack succeeded in a "miraculous" recovery after receiving treatment in the United Kingdom.
To 13-year-old Muhammad Ibrahim Khan, doctors in Pakistan had told him that he would never be able to walk again.
At least 140 people, most children, were killed when armed men attacked the Peshawar public school last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for surgery, will be discharged from the hospital later.
Exactly nine months ago, on an ordinary Tuesday morning, Mohamed sat in first aid class and listened carefully to his teachers.
Right then, seven armed men disguised as security guards entered the army's public school.
They wore explosive belts and had a simple mission to do: to kill all the men, women and children who came their way.
"I can't forget what happened that day," Mohamed says with a sharp look.
I was sitting in the auditorium, asking questions... and then I heard gunshots outside.
The terrorists went inside and started killing. Our teacher was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he pulled four students out of the amphitheater while the carnage was taking place.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, calling out to him.
He said, "Oh, brother, save me."
I held his hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he was shot in the head.
Most of those killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Muhammad's arms.
Mohamed remembers that right after that he passed out and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the waist down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then those in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to walk again.
"When I saw him, I felt my soul come out," says Sher Khan, Muhammad's father.
Those nine months were the hardest of my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son could never use his legs again.
They campaigned for help from Pakistani television, attracting the support of famous people like Imran Khan, a cricket player who became a politician.
Eventually, they managed to raise funds to take Muhammad to the United Kingdom and offer him treatment at the private Harley Street clinic in London.
Neurosurgeon consultant Irfan Malik described Muhammad as "scared" when he arrived at the hospital.
"He had spent the last few months lying in bed, unable to move from side to side, says Malik.
He was weak, there was a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in good shape.
A vertebra at the base of Muhammad's spine had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in the shoulder, hip, and back during the attack, and his lower spine had been destroyed, resulting in paralysis.
But during a six-hour operation, Malik and his team were able to retrace the nerve endings and rebuild the damaged part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised by what happened next.
Just a week after the operation, Mohamed got up and started taking steps and walking.
We didn't expect such a good result.
It was a miracle," he says.
Within two weeks of the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and begin the long recovery process.
Mohamed defied fate and began to walk again
He wants to become strong and continue his studies in the UK.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, join the army and fight terrorism.
"I feel like I still have a chance at life," he says, showing pictures of guns he drew next to school textbooks and pens
Physically, Mohamed is getting stronger every day, but the psychological trauma he's going through and now it's unimaginable.
"My anger has not fallen," he confesses.
Little kids were killed in my school.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes off a tear, caresses the head, and says, "I see my son walking again."
He will be able to continue his life naturally.
