Steven Wilson: "If I don't do anything, I feel guilty."
Steven Wilson has recently been named the Grand Winner of the Progressive Music Awards
Steven Wilson has often been called the most hardworking musician in the progressive rock world.
The talented musician won three awards at the Progressive Music Awards, which took place this month in London, including the Best Album Award of the Year for Hand.
In his five-star review, The Guardian called the album "a work of intelligent, expressive and captivating art".
Since the 1980s, Wilson has been the engine of several musical projects, the best known being the rock band Porcupine Tree.
Now, before two indoor shows at Royal Albert Hall, Wilson launches a double vinyl LP, Transience, to show the "more accessible" side of his solo activity.
He told the BBC about his love of vinyl and his busy schedule and explained how comedian Matt Berry came to open his shows.
What does vinyl mean to you?
I grew up right in the end of the vinyl era, and I remember then I was looking forward to the CD, because vinyl was so annoying.
You were buying a record, you were going home with him, he had a scratch on him, and you had to bring him back.
I love CDs, and for some types of music, like classical music, they're better than vinyl.
But the problem with CDs and digital downloads is that there is nothing left that you really value.
Having a vinyl is like having a nice painting hanging in your living room.
It's something you can hold in your hand, while you let yourself get sucked into the lyrics and overwhelmed by the artistic act.
I thought it was just a nostalgic thing, but there's no way it could be if kids too young to remember vinyls like that kind of experience.
Do you have any vinyl you particularly care about?
I admit I got rid of all the vinyls in the '90s.
All the vinyls I have are bought again.
I started from the idea of redoing the collection I had when I was 15, but I crossed that line.
The first record I convinced my parents to buy me was Out of the Blue from Electric Light Orchestra.
If I still had the original, it would have sentimental value, but unfortunately, it's somewhere in a charity store.
Steven Wilson hopes the album will be a gateway to possible new fans
Why did you launch your new Transience vinyl compilation?
This was originally conceived as an idea for record store day, but we missed the opportunity.
My label had suggested that I collect some of my shorter and more accessible songs.
I came to be slightly obsessed with the idea of doing something like "introduction into Steven Wilson's music," and I really wanted the project to be launched on vinyl alone.
Whoever buys vinyl also receives a downloaded high-resolution variant.
Are you worried that the album won't show your music in its true light?
No, because although I am focusing on longer music, there is one thing that I have always cherished above all else: the melodic part.
There is much progressive rock that focuses on technical complexity rather than the melodic side.
Pink Floyd, the most famous progressive rock band of all time, passed the test of time because they always stressed the melodic side and the atmosphere.
What are you preparing for the Albert Hall shows?
I don't want to reveal too much.
The repertoire will be completely different every one of the nights.
In the first, there will be a version of the Hand show. It was. which we had this year, but on steroids, with a few guests.
The second night will be more of a foray into my history, which is more focused on the fans who have been watching me over the years.
How did you choose Matt Berry to open your show on the second night?
And me and the rest of the tour team are big fans of [Channel 4 comedy series] Toast of London, to the point where we quote it all the time.
I thought I'd listen to Matt's music, so I bought him the album, Music for Insomniacs.
I talked to him about our mutual love for Mike Oldfield and asked him to play at the Royal Albert Hall.
It seems to me I'm extremely lucky to have him open.
You remixed albums by bands like XTC, Tears for Fears and Yes.
How much does that affect your own music?
I am not consciously inspired by this, but inevitably, when you deconstruct these classic albums, they remain in your mind.
My last solo album, The Raven That Refused to Sing, was undoubtedly the most progressive old school album I've ever created.
I don't think it was a coincidence that we had remixed King Crimson, Jethro Tull and Yes almost all last year.
The current album, Hand. Erase., is much more open, because I had worked at Tears for Fears and XTC.
You are often described as the busiest progressive rock musician.
Is that how you feel?
You can phase out the word progressively.
I think I'm probably one of the most obsessed people in the music world today, and I'm not saying this with pride, because please believe me, it's a curse.
I think I inherited this from my father, who has an incredibly powerful work ethic.
If I don't do anything all day, I start feeling guilty.
That's why working on remixes was a gift, because it means I don't always have to do just my music.
The music industry is a tough place to make a career.
Now I wouldn't recommend that to anyone as a profession.
I work daily and I'm not rich, but I live well.
I love what I do, it's a privilege, but if I were lazy, I don't think I would have survived.
Transience will be launched in the UK on 25 September.
Steven Wilson will perform at the Royal Albert Hall on 28 and 29 September, as part of his 2015-2016 European tour.
