A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new reference study, more than 3 million people a year die prematurely from external air pollution, more than from malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is burning wood and coal for home heating and cooking, but research reveals that agricultural emissions from Europe and the US are just as alarming as the main cause of these deaths.
The report warns that unless action is taken, the number of deaths - already equivalent to six deaths per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should sound an alarm for public health agencies around the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, environmental health expert at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by air rain are caused by tiny particles that can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause heart attack and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory disease.
The research did not include the effects of indoor air pollution, for example from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause 3.4 million more deaths per year.
The new study, published in the newspaper Nature, was the first to highlight various sources of external air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths they cause, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computer model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on the various populations, including new information on how pollution affects the inhabitants of China and India.
One third of all premature deaths were the result of using smoke-extinguishing fuels, such as wood and coal, for heating homes or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which are recognised dangers.
Consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India's 645 000 annual deaths and one third of China's 1.4 million annual deaths.
However, research has found that ammonia agricultural emissions have had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld of the Max Planck Chemical Institute in Germany, which led the research.
One fifth of all deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and the excess use of fertilisers.
Ammonia reacts with exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, the main cause of death due to air pollution in the eastern US, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," Lelieveld says.
Throughout the UK, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of the dead, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of deaths worldwide, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by power plants, especially coal-operated ones, has been significant globally, causing one in seven deaths.
In the US, it is the main single factor, causing one third of the 55 000 deaths annually, compared to 16% in the UK.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid and dusty regions, has caused almost a fifth of the global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, responsible for 92% of the deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"The overlap between the high level of pollution and the large number of inhabitants speaks out on public health, but there is little known about the sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths," Jerrett says.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health at global level.
All particles are now believed to be equally toxic.
But if those caused by the combustion of fuels are more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths attributable to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "the discovery is very valuable ... because agriculture was not generally seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and because it suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and political leaders".
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmospheric specialist at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom, said: "The study really highlights the need for air quality control to avoid these deaths, especially in highly populated areas of Asia".
