The region that is crawling with millionaires.
The Asian-Pacific millionaires will form, this year, the group of the richest people in the world, thanks to the wealth accumulated in China and India, a study published by Capgemini and RBC Wealth Management on Wednesday.
According to this document, in 2015, the accumulated wealth of Asian Pacific millionaires will exceed the total of $15,800 billion recorded in 2014, as well as the wealth of North American millionaires, who currently represent the richest people in the world, with a cumulative wealth of $16,200 billion, the AFP submits.
The study states that the Asia Pacific region already has the largest number of very rich people, named in financial jargon High Net Worth Individuals, HNWI, with 4.69 million of these individuals in 2014, compared to 4.68 million in North America.
HNWI are people who can invest at least a million dollars, without taking into account the value of real estate and other possessions.
"In the future, the wealth of HNWI is expected to grow more in Asia Pacific than in any other region of the world, with most of the new assets coming from emerging economies of China, India, Indonesia and Thailand," says the study by Capgemini and RBC Wealth Management.
The report estimates that China and India account for almost 10% of the global wealth of HNWI and are responsible for 17% of the global growth of new assets after 2006.
China, the world's second economy after the US, had in 2014 890,000 millionaires with a cumulative wealth of $4,500 billion, increasing by 17.5% and 19.3%, respectively, compared to 2013.
India, in turn, has the fastest pace of increasing the number of millionaires, 26.3%, up to 198,000 people, while their cumulative wealth has increased by 28.2%, up to 785 billion dollars.
