After a close four-hour meeting with prime ministers in the 16 federal states, Merkel said "the most important thing now is to create an orderly and transparent process to cope with the large number of refugees," the DPA agency notes.
She added that the federal government would create 40,000 seats for initial arrivals, as well as distribution centers.
"Such pivot points are needed," she stressed.
The whole country must provide a massive boost to cope with the crisis, Merkel added.
The Länder's prime ministers sought more help than the 6 billion euros agreed by the federal government coalition more than a week ago.
Turkish Prime Minister Bodo Ramelow of the Left Party asked for a "at least double and for commitments to be accelerated", in comments to a local newspaper.
In turn, the Prime Minister of Rhineland-Palatinate, Malu Dreyer, insisted that migrants be quickly integrated into German society.
"We need a national pact between all players, not only the federal government, states and municipalities, but also businesses, unions and civil society," she said.
Dreyer also called for bureaucracy in the manipulation of refugees and migrants to be accelerated.
She noted that Switzerland had completed processing in 48 hours and the Netherlands in 11 days, while Germany needed more than 5 months.
Prime Minister of Bavaria Horst Seehofer expressed similar feelings.
So far, Bavaria carries the most heavy burden, with most migrants arriving after crossing the Austrian border.
Seehofer, a powerful actor on the federal stage as head of the Christian-Social Union (CSU), a key component of the federal coalition government, came into public conflict with Merkel after the chancellor announced a virtual door policy opened at the beginning of the month, DPA recalls.
