Radu Gyr and Eliade
Following the description of some tabs from the "directory" of Mircea Eliade's political sympathies of youth, which, however condensed they may be, exceed the size of a daily article and must be broadcast in the series, deserves, I think, evoked the friendship between Radu Gyr and Mircea Eliade, one of the most vehement counts used by the detractors of the great Romanian scientist.
A less humorous description would, I hope, be useful in the real debate that the recent law, called "antilegionary", would be appropriate to stir it up in the Romanian intellectual environment.
Critically analyzing the various versions that spoke of Eliade's regigitation in the Legion through the Axis Nest and Radu Gyr, Florin Turcanu brings it up in the Mircea Eliade volume.
The prisoner of history (Bucharest, 2003), another hypothesis, which interests us to the highest degree in understanding the resumption of epistollary contacts between Radu Gyr and Eliade in 1968, after playing Ceausescu "the stage of the balcony" in August that year.
Based on documents signed by Radu Gyr under pressure, during the safety investigation, in 1941, documents kept today in the SRI archive (FD, Case 573, f.15) as well as on a follow-up note in 1938, Florin Turcanu states that "Eliade will not enter their group, but in the so-called "Leonary Family" called Luminita, a group of "cloves" by intellectuals, especially writers, led by poet Radu Gyr".
As regards Luminita's nest there are no verifiable data, those in exile considering the existence of this questionable "legionary family", what needs to be discussed is, after all, the context in which this information was recorded in the file.
Leaving aside the surprising courtesy of the SRI to make available these secret files to Mr Turcanu, it is more than obvious that, at the time, the aim of the pursuit of Safety was "commander" Radu Gyr, Eliade's mention being made, according to the note of 21 March 1938, in the context that Armand Călinescu, the Minister of Interior had been given a free hand to take all the necessary steps so that King Charles could impose the Royal Dictator, suspending his parliamentary life and eliminating the main political force of the legionaries who were beginning to enjoy unexpected popularity (The All-for-Country Party had emerged third in the 1937 elections).
Eliade's arrest was made as a result of this note, quoted by Turcanu: "Eliad Mircea, writer and journalist, joined the Legionary Movement in 1935 in the group of writers and poets under the leadership of Professor Radu Demetrescu Gyr".
As far as I am concerned, I see this note as a thin bureaucratic cover for the crackdown of 1938, and it is likely that such superficial notes were made at speed for the vast majority of legionaries or sympathizers active in the public space who needed to be arrested, but who needed to be tied to an important legionary leader.
Radu Gyr's above-mentioned ollograph statement, given in custody in February 1941, after the suppression of the legionary rebellion, only confirms in retrospect the first, the banal method of bureaucratic coverage in any police regime, authoritarian.
It would have been interesting if Turcanu had provided more details about the contents of the quoted 573 file.
Was that Eliade's file or Radu Gyr's?
Because anyway it has to be a file built on the basis of Safety documents, but then processed by Security to be used either against one or against the other.
There is an equivocal here, as in the case of the use of the term "member" of the Movement, which only one who knows the composition of the internal structures of this radical organization based on a religious foundation knows that it represents a pre-trial stage in which the one in question behaves as an active sympathizer, during the three-year trial period before becoming a "camerado" with fine acts.
Also, all these secondary forms of organization, such as intellectual clubs or censorships, sitters, discussion groups with peasants, youth organizations or students, revolved around a nest, were his "family", were not the nest itself, as a form of political organization and action.
This kind of nuances escape completely to the unsuspected lecturer, making Eliade's "member" status (which can be plausible) understood and used ad literam to designate political regulation in the nest.
Of course, the invocation of subtleties of interpretation of this kind cannot occultize the public activity of supporting the Guard or the clear sympathy for the Captain who animated Eliade in 1935-1940, whether in the wake of Nae Ionescu or not.
Public support for a cause in which you believe does not necessarily mean political regulation, however, all the more so since, as a rule, intellectuals of this scale preserve a type of superiority over activists as such and do not enter politics unless they are offered directly high privileges.
As much as I could form an opinion about Eliade's type of thinking from that time when he was the leader of the younger generation, I find it hard to believe that he would have accepted the hierarchical rigors in a legionary nest.
And Radu Gyr didn't have Nae Ionescu's intellectual ascendant, though!
Not to mention, only in passing, the fact that in any legionary "directory", what comes first is the anti-Semitic public activity as well as the violence, both worthy of being stigmatized, but nonexistent in Eliade's case, until further evidence.
As for Eliade-Gyr's correspondence between 1968 and 1969, Mircea Handoca, an enthusiastic defender of Eliade, tries to sanction Florin Turcanu's claims (although based on archive documents, even if they were worth dissecting and contextualizing more seriously) with a questionable argument.
Mircea Handoca notes, in the volume Noi Glosse on Mircea Eliade (Bucharest, 2006), that "no line of correspondence between Mircea Eliade and Radu Gyr contains any hint of this assignment".
There was no way that in 1968, when Radu Gyr, somehow, came out of the communist chambers, could not have risked any hint in a letter that was obviously intercepted by censorship.
What I think he wanted to point out to Mircea Handoca is that the tone of these letters that Radu Gyr sent was a respectful one, of admiration and affection without any doubt about Eliade's ascension.
There is really no such thing as the palest suggestion that Radu Gyr would ever have been Eliade's boss.
Smart, the poet forced to write at the Voice of Motherland, reveals from the very beginning his embarrassing condition by signaling Eliade (who knew very precisely what mission the publication that had been constantly dealing with the denigration of right-wing exile) in signature, after "your old friend", what to expect and is visibly relieved and happy when he responds affectionately after almost three decades of separation since the "stricken time" alienated them.
There is no doubt that, beyond the "mission" with which he had been tasked (to convince Eliade that now, in the new Romania, he could come back at least to see his mother and friends again) and that, skillfully, he also fulfills through short sentences, separated by paragraphs, to suggest their character as a foreign body, Radu Gyr only shows interest in literature.
There is no esoteric innuendo, of refined political complications suggested or of any evocation of the years of youth in a register other than the cultural one.
It is hard to believe that Radu Gyr would have been superior on Eliade's legionary line, but until the consolidation of this version with less circumstantial evidence than those offered by Florin Turcanu, we have in this correspondence shards of memory that testify to a mutual appreciation of characters who have marked differently, but steadfastly, our culture and who, beyond the dire attempts of life, find the tone of civilization and interwar education.
Important human and cultural documents and, why not?, illustrating for the strength of friendship and mutual respect beyond the "under the weather" destiny of the authors.
In the early 1970s, Eliade finally gave up refugee status by obtaining American citizenship and, under the pretext of health problems and catastrophic floods in the country, announced the RSR authorities, through the embassy (with which he wore a sporadic correspondence used to obtain passport for his sister), that he could not follow the invitation to return to the country.
The result was predictable: it is again placed at the index, it is mounted in Israel "The Toladot affair", the books sent to family and friends (Fragments d'un journal, Gallimard, 1973) are stopped by censorship, never sees its mother again.
Of the friends in the country only Noica has a sporadic correspondence, although surprisingly, as the personal archive in Chicago attests, a lot of individuals or Romanian institutions still manage to send messages.
Clearly why Radu Gyr didn't get permission to write to him after 1969.
And after 1977, when the Ceaușescu regime tried Eliade's second convincing operation (through official invitations, Noica's actions, translations, etc.) Radu Gyr had already passed into eternity.
