Twins Reunited After Almost 70 Years
Gemini George Skrzynecky and Lucian Poznanski, 69, were born at the end of World War II in Germany, after their Polish mother had just been released from a labor camp.
As she was too ill to care for them, the twins were sent to Poland for adoption, so the two brothers were separated not only from the one who gave them life, but from each other.
Tens of years George and Lucian didn't know about each other's existence.
At the age of 17, George discovered documents demonstrating that he was adopted and had a brother.
In the 1960s, he asked the Red Cross to help him find his brother, but they found no trace to lead them to Lucian.
Only in 2015, thanks to the Red Cross's "Restoring Family Links" program, the twins met again, and the moment was more than touching.
BBC reporters have captured this episode.
