Secondly, because I remember perfectly the same day from my childhood; then a story began that, as a matter of fact, has not yet ended.
I wasn't exactly what's usually called a conscientious student.
On the contrary, I would say.
But the school always liked me.
So much so that I chose to continue to attend it, even as a teacher.
When I decided this was what I wanted to do my whole life, I knew it wasn't an easy job.
And none with any stake.
That's because, like every one of us, I've come across all kinds of teachers: better or worse, nicer or unbearable, smarter or really stupid.
Unfortunately, there are people with other calls in this guild.
I think they're toxic, because they damage the enthusiasm and even the mind of a young man willing to form.
I was lucky to give, as I was a student or student, over a few, few, exceptional teachers.
These meetings can be decisive if they happen at the right time.
Who thinks that the role of the department is the banal transmission of some information is wrong.
This can be done by anyone; to inform, the student can inform himself very well that we are only living in the era of transparency.
A good teacher, however, shapes the minds of alumni.
It makes them, it makes them think.
Sitting in the chair is not a privilege, as many believe, but a great responsibility.
Young people are very picky, demanding, unforgiving and always willing to look for the problems of those in front of them.
That's how age dictates their temper.
As a teenager, we all thought we knew everything, that we had absolute certainty about everything.
When we grow up, we come to understand that we have nothing but doubts.
Therefore, the role of a teacher is to remove the adolescent from his self-sufficiency and make him think.
I mean, learn to doubt, to ask questions.
To discover on their own the answers, even the provisional ones.
To get involved in everything he does.
To lead him discreetly to profitable models.
It's very difficult, especially since most of the time the student believes that the teacher is his enemy.
One who can't wait to catch him on the wrong foot to sanction him.
However, this justifies him, the one who is always misunderstood, rebellious, who owes a lot of time to live up to his age calls, to look at the one in the department with suspicion.
It's just that he can't accept naturally his attempt to order it.
Adolescents shall not be allowed to work out, do not accept restrictions.
Or if they feel like they're doing it, they're getting revenge somehow.
And unfortunately, when there is a rigid person in the department, who imposes himself through hardness and does not communicate, the students take revenge on the object taught.
There are thousands of such teenagers who miss meetings with great writers, for example, because of the lack of tact of the Romanian teacher.
There are thousands of such students who think that history is a collection of data, that mathematics are the most exhausting for their unripe minds.
I always urge my students: if you find a teacher that you don't swallow, who doesn't know how to communicate with you from man to man, don't let him push you away from the literature that he should direct you to.
How did it happen that I became the teacher myself?
I had a really good teacher in VI-VIII.
He has opened my mind to some texts that have spoken to the puberty since then in his own understanding.
I met a professor in high school who opened the door to his library.
I looked at him as a man from another world: he had the walls of his house covered with bookshelves.
I'd get lost in his library and dream about having one of my own.
I may have it now, but if fate hadn't put it in my way, maybe I'd have decided to become a football player.
Or an engineer or a lawyer or whatever.
I don't think dating like this is random.
I don't believe in chance.
The main thing is to come across the man who takes your hand and patiently directs you to your own vocation.
And this is, most of the time, the teacher.
Now, my experience only helps me talk about what it means to teach literature.
It's just that literature can't teach.
There is no such thing as a professor of literature, as there is a teacher of mathematics.
How to fix the ineffable in concepts?
You can, at most, approximate it, without pretending to transmit petrified truths.
The one at the department can guide the reading at best, that's something else.
But especially can occasion some miraculous encounters between a reader and some books.
There are meetings that can change the life of the person in the bank.
There are meetings that can open his mind, that can lift someone's voice, scales off his eyes.
Therefore, the literature teacher must first manage to make his students understand (feel) that there is no divorce between literature and life.
On the contrary!
A great coseur, Al. Paleologu, said one thing only apparently paradoxical: "How much literature, so much life, not the other way around!" and he was right.
That's why a good teacher prepares you for life, doesn't make you a specialist in an open field anyway.
Fortunately, there's always something to learn.
And we, the teachers; or especially us, the teachers.
Most of the time, a great truth is repeated only from inertia: not only do the disciples have to learn from their masters, but also vice versa.
Ideally, the teacher should be a master and the student an apprentice.
Who, like every valuable young man, leaves his master when he discovers his own way.
Few find him, that's right.
But it was the master who lit the spark.
I don't think there's any greater happiness for a pure-blooded teacher than to endure as many of these breakups as possible.
