Justice in the United States and Switzerland will proceed to new arrests
US and Swiss authorities have announced that new individuals and organisations will be prosecuted as part of the investigation into corruption in FIFA, international media reports.
US Justice Minister Loretta Lynch announced at a press conference in Zurich on Monday that the scope of investigations into corruption in world football was widened.
"On the basis of our co-operation and on the basis of new evidence, we will commit additional prosecutions against new individuals and organisations," Lynch said.
In May, several senior FIFA officials were arrested in Switzerland in the case of corruption.
Many of them have already been extradited to the United States.
"We have hopes that other people will also be prosecuted in the US," Lynch added.
Switzerland's Attorney General Michael Lauber, also present at the press conference, said his institution had seized several assets, including homes and land in the Alps, as well as financial assets, in the investigation carried out in collaboration with the US.
"We haven't even reached the end of the first half," Lauber said.
So far, a huge amount of information, 11 terrabytes, has been confiscated.
At the same time, 121 bank accounts are being investigated.
An agreement to cede media rights to the 2010 World Cups in South Africa and in 2014 - Brazil has also entered the investigators' attention.
FIFA faces a big corruption scandal after US justice has indicted 14 people, including two FIFA vice-presidents and seven forum officials.
Retained persons are being investigated for bribery and other benefits, from the early 1990s to the present, totalling over $150 million.
Following this scandal, Swiss Joseph Blatter announced in early July that he was resigning as FIFA president after being re-elected for the fifth time.
