Justice Minister Robert Cazanciuc said, at the opening of the school year at the Craiova Detention Center, that the youngest student is 15 years old and is in the first grade and the oldest is 25 years old and is in the 11th grade, showing that they could have another life if they went to school.
I chose to participate in the opening of the school year in a center belonging to the National Administration of Penitentiaries to try to draw attention, and in this way, to some less known realities.
The youngest student, aged 15, is enrolled in the first class, and the oldest is 25 years old and is enrolled in the 11th grade.
"There are complicated topics that society is concerned about debating at this point, we are all pressed by our own worries and problems, but we must not overlook the lesson that these over 100 young people in the Craiova Detention Centre offer," Minister Robert Cazanciuc said at the opening ceremony of the school year on Monday.
The Minister of Justice pointed out that the lack of education, motivated in many cases by the lack of material possibilities, can lead to tragedies, stating that the young people in this centre would have had another chance in life if they could have taken the natural course of any child, if they had the opportunity to learn not only to write, read, but also to receive a set of moral values, to find out what it means to observe the law and what consequences it may have.
"The role of the prison system is not to permanently isolate from society people who have broken the law, to close them behind high walls, but to try to re-educate and prepare them, so that when they return to the community they have more chances of reintegration," Cazanciuc added.
The minister made it clear that it is necessary to invest in schools, hospitals, roads, but investments must also be made in the prison system, because in many cases detention conditions are borderline humane and because, in the absence of money and staff, it will be difficult to talk about the reintegration of convicted persons.
We work very well with the Ministry of Education and thanks to this partnership, every year, in the prison system, there are over 2000 graduates of school courses.
