The red flag has gone up
The internal Labour Scrutiny seems more spectacular and politically significant, as the newly elected leader automatically becomes its spearhead in the upcoming elections.
Raised, therefore, the red-lit flag / Under its folds we will live and die.
That's what Jeremy Corbyn sang yesterday in the London Sanctuary House pub.
He's witnessed a lot of facts and vows. Let's not change his color now.
Readers who do not know the melodic line of this unofficial anthem of the British and international left (The Red Flag) can search for it on the Internet and would not be excluded from having a surprise.
With our heads exposed, let's all swear that we'll wear it until we collapse.
The author of these lines is not at all an admirer of the red flags (and those who wave them), but he respects the democratic political traditions built around them.
If Jeremy Corbyn succeeds in joining yesterday's left and tomorrow's left, this love story between him and the base of the Labour Party will have a happy ending.
I do not believe that this will happen, but it seems premature to talk about the great and inevitable electoral defeat, five years from now, of a leader elected the day before yesterday.
Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have seen an impressive democratic exercise.
It was not the British laborers who invented the system of direct voting for the party leader among the Western left.
French Socialists have been practicing a more complicated motion-based system for several years that allows for the expression of all members and sympathizers; in addition, they have organised a preliminary competition for the nomination of the presidential candidate since 2012.
However, the internal Labour elections seem more spectacular and politically significant, as the newly elected leader automatically becomes its spearhead in the upcoming elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, with the customisation of power being more pronounced in Britain than on the other side of the English Channel.
In addition, the turnout was high in all three "circles": members of the actual trade unions and other organizations affiliated to the party and, finally, the group of sympathizers (who received the ballot after a summary registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting information about the perceptions of left-wing segments in British society, especially those made up of young people or middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to become even more involved in the future, precisely because of the signal given by Corbin's victory.
There are, as far as I know, sociological investigations that tell us too much about the attitudes of this "outer circle" labor, so cautious speculation is allowed.
I think we find enough attitudes similar to those of Podemos sympathisers (Spain) or even Syriza (Greece), with the observation that they will go through the traditional channels of the left.
If we want to identify an "antisystem" vocation, it is reflected primarily by the rejection of the centrist line, New Labour (for many, only a hidden form of the much-hulite thatcherism).
The second component would be to repudiate the leaders deemed guilty of the two successive electoral failures, one argument being that they did not go to the left sufficiently, that they did not delineate firmly from the Tony Blair era.
The second landmark - even more suggestively, according to me - is offered by the recent referendum on Scotland's independence.
If we disregard the separatist message and focus strictly on aspirations on other political topics, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of public segments favourable to the social state and animated by the aspiration of equity, adept at disarmament and hostile to military involvement abroad, but also sensitive to the new themes of the left: ecology, gender, assistance for poor countries.
The Scottish laborists thus lost a electorate to which they should have, at least in principle, had privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm for Corbin's campaign).
Such energies exist all over the UK, but the old leadership couldn't attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation as an outsider, has more chances of success than Ed Miliband, the Labour "aristocrate".
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I think, than the one with the anti-system left on the southern outskirts of Europe.
The term "antisystem" is too harsh: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
By next week, we will learn more about the first steps of Jeremy Corbyn, as the leader of the opposition.
We will see if the Red Flag will also ring in the House of Commons (it would not be the first time) after the new leader has taken his place, primarily of the opposition banks.
However, what Jeremy Corbin now wants from his fellow Members in Parliament is first and foremost unity - and in this regard he does have reason to be concerned.
