On the contrary, he's a fighter against Al Assad for democracy and all that.
"So you could add rude manipulation to the painting"!
I have to admit, I felt bad.
All the more so since while I wrote the article, it occurred to me to check the story of the former warrior and "Syrian rebel commander Laith Al-Saleh" in the second part of the space dedicated by V. Marin to his person "jihadist Laith Al-Saleh" (the two categorisations - "rebel" and "jihadist" - could in itself make me from the start circumspect).
Because I trusted the truth, his journalists.
On the spot, I had no further comment on Marius Cristian's pull of the sleeve than this: "I need it if I (had) confidence in the truth"
After that, I obviously took the story for granted and I feel indebted to readers with the correct presentation of the story of Syrian Laith Al-Saleh.
The oldest I found was in an Associated Press material (Syrian rebel leader seeks Europe - Syrian rebel leader seeks Europe) signed by Nicholas Bahitis and Dalton Bennett on 17 August 2015 on the island of Kos in Greece, where they noticed, among the hundreds, perhaps thousands of refugees, a man trying to clean up the chaos of the crowd.
The man was Syrian scholar Laith Al Saleh of Aleppo who "is accustomed to being in command", since he "led a unit of 700 rebels in the Syrian Civil War".
We also learn that Al Saleh, 30, had "a home, a wife and a normal life before the battle began that cost more than 250,000 lives and put a third of Syria's population on the road".
In an interview with correspondents at the Associated Press, Al Saleh tells that "everyone wants to leave Syria".
My city is the most dangerous city in the world.
About 70% of the city is destroyed.
In Syria, Al Qaeda wants me, Daesh (an extremist group of the Islamic State) wants me, the government wants me - I fought against everyone.
Beyond being kicked out of a supermarket on the island, Kos would have offered him "an even more sinister meeting - with a man in whom he recognized a Syrian enemy": "Two days ago, I saw a sniper from government forces.
I didn't talk to him, but I'm still very upset.
From the material we also learn that Laith (meaning lion in Arabic) was indeed on his way to Holland, where he had a cousin - former senior officer in the Syrian army and then became also rebellious and arrived in the West after he was seriously injured - hoping to obtain asylum and then bring his family - wife and a three-year-old boy (nearly an age with the civil war in Syria, which broke out in March 2011).
After this was achieved, Laith Al-Saleh would not have ruled out a return to Syria to continue the fight for the Syrian Free Army (supported by the West) - against three forces: President Bashar Assad's army (supported by the Russians), the Islamic State and the Al-Qaeda-affiliated Nusra Front.
A madness - who wants freedom must fight in Syria against not one enemy, but three!
I also came across a Serbian material on August 22nd, of which I did not understand much, except that Laith Al Saleh is associated with terrorists who come along with migrants: TERRORISTS KRIJU MIGU MIGRANTIMA calls the headline of a news on http://www.telegraf.rs/vest, in which a picture of Al Saleh with a beard is joined holding a Syrian flag and that of refugee wearing a THANK YOU shirt.
On September 7, then, on the BBC website itself, Mike Wendling drew attention to the case of manipulation with the help of photographs of the Syrian fighter: This viral photo falsely Claims to show an IS fighter possessing as a refugee - This viral picture claims wrongly to depict an Islamic State fighter posing as a refugee.
We learn that the picture (in fact: the picture - the one with Laith with the beard and the gun and the one with the THANK YOU shirt) was posted by a user on Facebook, which user would have apologized in the meantime.
Only before that, just from his wall, the image of the two pictures would have been cut over 70,000 times, gathering a few thousand comments.
That word, too late, the horse was gone!
In Romania, on September 9, Carla Dinu from Hotnews takes over the story of manipulation from the BBC, but mistranslates the title: "A fake photo turned viral shows an ISIS fighter posing as a refugee".
Obviously, it's not the photo that's fake, but the interpretation was false, wrong, in short: manipulative.
